04986nam a22008895i 9780520965577DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20162016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780520965577  a(DE-B1597)520380  a(OCoLC)961063192  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aGN484 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a392/.109667223  aLB 604652rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90577:9141 aHodzic, Saida, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Twilight of Cutting :bAfrican Activism and Life after NGOs /cSaida Hodzic. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface: Coming to Questions -- tIntroduction: Governmentality against Itself -- t1. Colonial Reason, Sensibility, and the Ethnographic Style -- t2. Making Harmful Traditional Practices -- t3. When Cutting Did and Did Not End -- t4. Mistaken by Design: Biopolitics in Practice -- t5. Blood Loss and Slow Harm in Times of Scarcity -- t6. The Feminist Fetish: Legal Advocacy -- t7. Against Sovereign Violence -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe last three decades have witnessed a proliferation of nongovernmental organizations engaging in new campaigns to end the practice of female genital cutting across Africa. These campaigns have in turn spurred new institutions, discourses, and political projects, bringing about unexpected social transformations, both intended and unintended. Consequently, cutting is waning across the continent. At the same time, these endings are misrecognized and disavowed by public and scholarly discourses across the political spectrum. What does it mean to say that while cutting is ending, the Western discourse surrounding it is on the rise? And what kind of a feminist anthropology is needed in such a moment? The Twilight of Cutting examines these and other questions from the vantage point of Ghanaian feminist and reproductive health NGOs that have organized campaigns against cutting for over thirty years. The book looks at these NGOs not as solutions but as sites of “problematization.” The purpose of understanding these Ghanaian campaigns, their transnational and regional encounters, and the forms of governmentality they produce is not to charge them with providing answers to the question, how do we end cutting? Instead, it is to account for their work, their historicity, the life worlds and subjectivities they engender, and the modes of reflection, imminent critique, and opposition they set in motion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aFemale circumcisionxPolitical aspectszGhana. 0aFemale circumcisionzGhanaxPrevention. 0aFeminismzGhana. 0aNon-governmental organizationsxSocial aspectszGhana. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aactivism.  aactivist.  aactivists.  aafrica.  aafrican continent.  aanthropology.  acultural.  afemale circumcision.  afemale genital cutting.  afemale genital mutilation.  afemale issues.  afeminist issues.  afeminist.  aghana.  agovernment.  ainternational.  ajustice.  alaw and order.  amutiliation.  angos.  apolitical.  apolitics.  aproblem solving.  areproductive health.  atradition.  awestern world.  awomens issues.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052029198040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965577423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965577/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of Califor